******
[2]
Date: Jan 27, 2010
Source: AP [edited]
<http://wbztv.com/wireapnewsnh/New.Hampshire.anthrax.2.1452669.html>


A woman who contracted a rare form of anthrax nearly 2 months ago
remains hospitalized but is now able to answer questions from state
health officials, the deputy state epidemiologist said Wednesday [27 Jan 2010].

Dr. Jodie Dionne-Odom wouldn't give details, but said the patient's
responses back up the theory that she swallowed anthrax spores
propelled into the air by drumming at the United Campus Ministry
building in Durham. The woman became ill shortly after the 4 Dec 2009
event and had been in critical condition with gastrointestinal anthrax.

Anthrax spores later were found on 2 animal skin-covered drums and 4
other locations in the ministry building, which houses 8 University
of New Hampshire students and a food pantry and is used as a meeting
place for numerous community groups. The ministry center's offices,
food pantry and students have been relocated since the anthrax
investigation began, but Dionne-Odom said they will be allowed to
return once the building is decontaminated.

The state has given the building's owners a detailed cleanup plan,
which includes hiring contractors to spend several weeks bleaching
and scrubbing 5 rooms in the building, and using special vacuum
cleaners, she said. "This is not cleaning anyone can do," she said.

Environmental Protection Agency investigators took more than 70
samples from the building earlier this month [January 2010].
Authorities had said previously that 4 came back with low levels of
anthrax and more than 10 were inconclusive. Those 10 have now been
determined to be negative, Dionne-Odom said.

Two recent U.S. anthrax cases also were traced to drums covered with
animal hides, but those involved spores that were either inhaled into
the lungs or entered through the skin of people who were exposed
while making drums. The gastrointestinal form usually occurs after
eating raw or undercooked meat.

[Byline: Holly Ramer]

